data.content:
Here is the full performance analysis.

---

## Scan Execution Checklist

| Recipe | Hits |
|--------|------|
| `.IndexOf(string)` w/o StringComparison | 0 |
| `.Substring(` | 0 |
| `.StartsWith/.EndsWith` w/o StringComparison | 0 |
| `.ToLower()/.ToUpper()` | 0 |
| `.ToLowerInvariant()` | 1 |
| `params` | 2 |
| `.Select/.Where/.Take/.Aggregate` (LINQ) | 16 |
| `.Any/.All` | 1 |
| `.ToList()` | 1 |
| `.ToArray()` | 1 |
| `new List<` | 1 |
| `[.. spread]` (materializing) | 2 |
| `Enum.ToString()` | 1 |
| Unsealed non-abstract classes | 1 of 1 |
| `new Regex(` / `RegexOptions.Compiled` | 0 |

---

## Findings

### 1. LINQ Chains in Hot-Path `Humanize()` Pipeline (9 instances)

🔴 **Critical**

**Impact:** Each LINQ method (`.Where`, `.Take`, `.Any`) allocates an enumerator object + a delegate. The `Humanize()` call path allocates **~7 enumerators + delegates per invocation**—at millions of calls/minute this is massive GC pressure.

**Files:**
`TimeSpanFormatting.cs:L128` (`.Any`), `L140` (`.Where`), `L143` (`.Take`), `L146` (`.Where`), `L149` (`[.. ]` spread→List), `L158` (`.Where().ToList()`), `L169` (`.Take`)

**Fix:** Replace with `foreach` loops and manual index tracking. The input is always a `List<string?>` with ≤8 elements—a simple loop is both faster and clearer:

```csharp
// Replace IsContainingOnlyNullValue (L127-128)
private static bool IsContainingOnlyNullValue(List<string?> timeParts)
{
    foreach (var part in timeParts)
        if (part != null) return false;
    return true;
}

// Replace SetPrecisionOfTimeSpan (L133-150)
private static List<string?> SetPrecisionOfTimeSpan(
    List<string?> timeParts, int precision, bool countEmptyUnits)
{
    var result = new List<string?>(precision);
    int count = 0;
    foreach (var part in timeParts)
    {
        if (count >= precision) break;
        if (!countEmptyUnits && part == null) continue;
        if (countEmptyUnits) count++;
        else count++;
        if (part != null) result.Add(part);
    }
    return result;
}

// Replace ConcatenateTimeSpanParts (L155-171) — accept List, avoid .Where().ToList()
private static string ConcatenateTimeSpanParts(
    List<string?> timeSpanParts, CultureInfo culture, string collectionSeparator)
{
    var parts = new List<string>(timeSpanParts.Count);
    foreach (var p in timeSpanParts)
        if (p != null) parts.Add(p);
    // ... rest unchanged
}
```

---

### 2. `Enum.ToString().ToLowerInvariant()` Per-Call Reflection (1 instance)

🔴 **Critical**

**Impact:** `Enum.ToString()` uses reflection and allocates a string on every call. `.ToLowerInvariant()` allocates a second string. Called once per non-zero time unit (up to 8× per `Humanize()` call). At millions of calls/min, this is a major allocation source.

**File:** `TimeSpanFormatting.cs:L175`

**Fix:** Cache the lowered names in a static array indexed by enum value:

```csharp
private static readonly string[] s_unitNames =
[
    "year", "month", "week", "day", "hour", "minute", "second", "millisecond"
];

private static string FormatTimePart(int value, TimeUnit unit, CultureInfo culture)
{
    var unitName = s_unitNames[(int)unit];
    return value == 1 ? $"{value} {unitName}" : $"{value} {unitName}s";
}
```

---

### 3. Wasteful List Allocation in Zero-Value Path (1 instance)

🟡 **Moderate**

**Impact:** `CreateTimePartsWithNoTimeValue("no time")[0] ?? "no time"` (L76) allocates a `List<string?>` only to immediately index element 0 and discard it.

**File:** `TimeSpanFormatting.cs:L74-77`

